<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-349-741  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 349 741.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  Feb 1989 v18 n2 p54(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber transmission extended to 3,700 miles - without repeaters.andO;(includes related article on groupware)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Strauss, Paul R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Researchers at Bell Laboratories have developed a new transmissiontechnique for optical pulses that stretches the distance betweenrepeaters to 3,700 miles.andP;  The transmission was achieved bypulsing light over silica single-mode fiber, but researchersrecommend using dispersion-shifted fiber for best results.andP;  Theonly problem with the technique is that it requires a100-milliwatt pump laser to periodically condition the fiber witha sideways blast of light.andP;  Such a laser is not likely to becommercially available for another few years.andP;  A specific opticalwave that can travel through glass lasers without dispersing, asoliton, is also used in the technique.andP;  The researchers hope toperform straight-line experiments and use real communicationssignals next.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Bell Laboratories Inc. (research).andO;Topic:     Fiber opticsRepeatersTechnologyWaveformsLasersTransmission LinesResearch and Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>